Class Player

java.lang.Object
  GameObject
      Player

public class Player
extends GameObject

Player represents the actual player in MazeRunner.

This class extends GameObject to take advantage of the already implemented location functionality. Furthermore, it also contains the orientation of the Player, ie. where it is looking at and the player's speed.

All these variables can be adjusted freely by MazeRunner. They could be accessed by other classes if you pass a reference to them, but this should be done with caution.

Observant developers would note that, except for the speed variable and its get and set methods, this class is nearly identical to the Camera class. Could the GameObject not incorporate the angle as well?
This implementation does not do this, because not all possible game objects have an orientation and thus the inherited functionality would be redundant. One could argue for another superclass, which implements the orientation functionality, but for a small application, this bogs it down with superclasses and generally makes the hierarchy of objects harder to understand.

Author:
Bruno Scheele

Constructor Detail

Player

public Player(double x,
              double y,
              double z,
              double h,
              double v)
The Player constructor.

This is the constructor that should be used when creating a Player. It sets the starting location and orientation.

Note that the starting location should be somewhere within the maze of MazeRunner, though this is not enforced by any means.

Parameters:
x - the x-coordinate of the location
y - the y-coordinate of the location
z - the z-coordinate of the location
h - the horizontal angle of the orientation in degrees
v - the vertical angle of the orientation in degrees
